				<wikidot:authorName>Pot-boiler</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2830465</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Archaic but very organised. Military kit is usually named in order of increasing detail. I.E. -<br /> Biscuits, brown<br /> Cheese, processed*<br /> Rifle, short, magazine, lee-Enfield<br /> Sight unit, infantry, trilux</p> <p>It's more like a drive/directory path than a street address, so better suited for storekeeping.</p> <p>*aka &quot;cheese possessed&quot;. Needs its own SCP&#8230;</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-649550#post-2523886</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-649550/scp-1817#post-2523886</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 14 Jun 2016 16:43:14 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>sirpudding</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>348648</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>A pun on &quot;mystery&quot;. In English it is possible, though generally archaic, to construct noun phrases of the form: [noun] [adjective]; this is still present in modern English in a few usages i.e., &quot;Court Martial&quot;. In this case it is a mist (a cloud of visible vapor) that is eerie (unsettling) which is being used to obscure something left deliberately mysterious (unknown).</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
